abstract.value: Peter V. Cacchione was a labor leader, communist and New York City councilman. He took advantage of New York City's proportional representation system, and ran (unsuccessfully) for city council on the Communist Party ticket in 1937 and 1939. He was elected in 1941, 1943 and 1945 and served until his death in 1947. The collection includes his correspondence, speeches, wiritings, clippings, etc. from 1936-1947. Researchers must use microfilm (R-7823), except for series V, Scrapbooks.

Donated by Dorothy Cacchione, 1978. The accession number associated with this gift is 1978.012.
<list><item>Simon W. Gerson. <title render="italic">Pete: the Story of Peter V. Cacchione, New York's First Communist Councilman</title>, New York: International Publishers, 1976.</item></list>
The last series consists of scrapbooks and loose material removed from scrapbooks (not microfilmed) documenting Cacchione's political career from 1939 to 1945.

Miscellaneous Documents and Materials1943-1947915Series V: Scrapbooks1939-194810-11Scope and Content Note

This series contains materials from disassembled scrapbooks. It includes clippings, election materials related to Cacchione's run for councilman, holiday cards, correspondence, event invitations and programs, flyers related to Communist Party campaigns and events, and articles by and about Cacchione. The series also contains an oversized Scrapbook which includes clippings, flyers, press releases, and a small number of photographs relating to Cacchione's political career.
